  "doc_id": "26570",
  "text": "The fourth identified targets for WNK4 are the proteins mediating parecellular Cl -flux in the distal nephron known as claudins. Two independent groups [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] observed simultaneously in MDCKII cells that WNK4 increases the paracellular transport of Cl -but not that of Na + . This effect requires WNK4 catalytic activity and is associated with phosphorylation of claudin 4 in its carboxyl-terminal domain. In addition, PHAII-type mutations in WNK4 are associated with a further increase in Cl -permeability and phosphorylation of claudin 4 ( table 2 ). Finally, WNK4 also inhibits the activity of the K-Cl cotransporters KCC1, KCC3 and KCC4 [52] , which in the distal nephron are critical for potassium secretion in the DCT [CITATION_3] and acid secretion in the CD [CITATION_4] . KCC4 knockout mice feature metabolic acidosis. The WNK4 inhibitory effect is kinase dependent but was not affected by PHAII-type mutations ( table 2 ) .",
